results.occurrenceRemarks: Gray Fox or Domestic Cat?  These are old tracks but they were made in soft clay. See how the second photo shows a slightly swirled track with tiny claws registering for toes 3 and 4.  The third photo shows a total of four tracks, including the first two. There are raccoon tracks in the photo as well, but they all point down and the fox tracks point up.  I originally thought these were fox tracks, but now I'm leaning towards Domestic Cat based on  a couple things. The distance between the claw marks and the toe pads on the second photo is too short for Gray Fox. And the toe pads are too spread out and long. I'm having trouble seeing enough detail in the palm pads to use those to tell.  What do you guys think?

results.occurrenceRemarks: Chartreux cats tend to be quiet, rarely making noises such as mewing or crying, and some are mute. They are quite observant and intelligent, with some Chartreux learning to operate radio on/off buttons and to open screen door latches. They take about two years to reach adulthood. Chartreux cats are playful cats well into their adult years; some can be taught to fetch small objects in the same manner as a dog. Chartreux are good with children and other animals. They are non-aggressive, affectionate, good travelers and generally very healthy. Chartreux tend to bond with one person in their household, preferring to be in their general vicinity (often following their favored person from room to room), though they are still loving and affectionate to the other members of the household.
